The pastries at Tartine are beautiful and taste similar to the ones I've had in France. I came here at night so I really want to come back in the morning when the pastries are fresh. I enjoyed what I had but I definitely want to try more.

Tartine, a legendary San Francisco bakery in the heart of San Francisco. Everything about this place screams San Francisco and just being in there and experiencing the ambience brings me joy. As most bread bakers (i'm really just an amateur), I have all their beautiful books on my shelf. I love thumbing through their recipes and looking at their beautiful pictures of well baked bread. Ever thought about getting creative with your bread scoring? Check out some of Tartine's creative designs. Tartine has several locations in the city but I think this is one of the most popular just by the number of reviews and the number of people lined up outside just as they opened. We came early anticipating that there would be a line and because we wanted to start our day early. There's not much space inside so you'll have to continue the line down the road. There's actually a fair number of seats for those who want to enjoy their pastry and coffee indoors but about 6 seats outside for those who want to brave the cool weather. When you step inside, you are instantly transported into an ole timey San Francisco setting. It's been a while since a fresh coat of paint has been put on the walls but yet it doesn't ruin your experience. Fresh baked bread lines the walls and while they have a beautiful cabinet filled with pastries, it's not at all lit that well. Again, just adding to the ambience they are setting. I found that to be oddly beautiful. Today I got myself and eclair (which was excellent), a frangipane croissant and a chocolate croissant. I was not impressed with the croissants. The croissant was good, the chocolate and frangipane were good but combined I didn't think it quite hit my mark. Clearly they make good bread but when I get something like the frangipane croissant I like it so buttered up it doesn't even resemble the croissant anymore. I think that's preference. I also got myself an espresso to start the day off but was also unfortunately disappointed as it was highly acidic and difficult to drink (almost needed a cube of sugar which I almost never do with my coffee). This wasn't quite the experience I hoped for. I love their recipes and I really think they are famous for a reason. However my one time trip for their croissants and their coffee left me unimpressed. Perhaps I should just stick with their bread. Their service was quick, efficient and welcoming but I'd think twice about going back for pastries alone.

I came here on a Saturday afternoon and the wait was about 15 mins long (not too bad!). They take orders pretty efficiently. We ordered a mix of pastries: croissants, a cheese bread, cookie, rye bar, and brownies. All were delicious and yummy. They do have seating available indoors and outdoors. If the seats are full, you can enjoy them at Dolores Park a few blocks away. Their pies and tarts look really good too. I will come back for those next time!

I came here with my sister for a day trip in San Francisco! We came at around 2pm, so the wait was only about 5 minutes! The line did still go out the door but it was a quick line. We just wanted a few pastries to go while we ventured next to explore the mission district. We ordered a macchiato, lemon cream tarts, croissant, and morning bun. The macchiato was fresh and delicious. The croissant was buttery and crunchy on the outside and so soft on the inside. The morning bun was original tasting because of the citrus flavors in it. None were warm at 2pm though. The lemon tarte was a little too tangy for my taste. Will try another tarte next time! Overall not a bad place but didn't quite necessarily knock my socks off - hence the 4/5 stars. Staff was very nice even though this is such a busy place. Presentation was great!

As usual the morning bun was super delicious! Also picked up my favorite bread pudding.

At the same time, how can ANY Yelp reviewer try to compare this bakery to others, grading it at anything below 4 stars? WTF. I live in Oak-town. For the same reason: Theirs is above everybody else's! Tartine's cookies are to die for. The Morning Buns and Almond Croissant are the best I've tasted anywhere (except for La Farine in Oakland! but that's a different story). The cakes here are dense, super rich, and decadent. The bread baked here is otherworldly. No Sh*t! The overall personality of their baked goods is dense, heavy, monumental, and intensely flavorful. All at the same time. Who else does that? No one. Yes, the crowd and lines here are ridiculous. Their prices are awfully high, too. So? Walk right in to other mediocre bakeries and have at it, then. All you would want. Cheaper too. Expect a short wait when coming to Tartine. This French bakery is a popular, cute corner shop with beautiful and delicious pastries. Each baked good I tried had different levels of flavor and complimentary textures. Food tried: 1) Banana Cream Tarte (5/5): I was super fortunate to get the last banana cream tart on a Sunday at 2:30pm. And note, this is not a banana cream pie, it is a tart. The thick cracker crust has a warm and sweet crunch to it. For the main filling on top of the crust, you have the creamy banana cream and many slices of freshanana 2) Morning Bun (5/5): Most people that come here order the morning bun. I see why! This worthy and hyped pastry is like a cinnamon roll croissant with an orange taste and coated in the perfect amount of cinnamon sugar. Love the flaky texture, and the refreshing and light orange flavor. Expect a wait when you come to Tartine but your tastebuds will be happily rewarded. Note: they also have fresh baked bread but that is only available after 4:30pm.

I've visited Tartine multiple times (usually on a weekend) and there's always a long line snaking outside the door. Crazy enough, I went Saturday around 2pm and there was no line to be seen! So winning! I think where Tartine really wins is in their ham and cheese croissant. I prefer the version without the jalapenos. They're huge and they have the perfect ratio of dough to ham to cheese. It's chewy and fluffy and crunchy all at the same time. at $6.50 a pop you can count on it being a full meal. I've had other things here as well but I don't think anything shines as much as the ham and cheese. The banana cream pie was okay. The crumble cake was meh, something you'd find at a diner. The worst for me is probably their bread pudding. I'm used to bread pudding being bready, soft, but not runny. Their bread pudding seemed more like a steamed egg. There was too much egg that it was overwhelming and wasting like an steamed egg tart scramble with fruit toppings. Pass on the bread pudding and go straight for the croissants!

    Tartine, a legendary San Francisco bakery in the heart of San Francisco. Everything about this place screams San Francisco and just being in there and experiencing the ambience brings me joy. As most bread bakers (i'm really just an amateur), I have all their beautiful books on my shelf. I love thumbing through their recipes and looking at their beautiful pictures of well baked bread. Ever thought about getting creative with your bread scoring? Check out some of Tartine's creative designs. Tartine has several locations in the city but I think this is one of the most popular just by the number of reviews and the number of people lined up outside just as they opened.

    We came early anticipating that there would be a line and because we wanted to start our day early. There's not much space inside so you'll have to continue the line down the road. There's actually a fair number of seats for those who want to enjoy their pastry and coffee indoors but about 6 seats outside for those who want to brave the cool weather. When you step inside, you are instantly transported into an ole timey San Francisco setting. It's been a while since a fresh coat of paint has been put on the walls but yet it doesn't ruin your experience. Fresh baked bread lines the walls and while they have a beautiful cabinet filled with pastries, it's not at all lit that well. Again, just adding to the ambience they are setting. I found that to be oddly beautiful.

    Today I got myself and eclair (which was excellent), a frangipane croissant and a chocolate croissant. I was not impressed with the croissants. The croissant was good, the chocolate and frangipane were good but combined I didn't think it quite hit my mark. Clearly they make good bread but when I get something like the frangipane croissant I like it so buttered up it doesn't even resemble the croissant anymore. I think that's preference. I also got myself an espresso to start the day off but was also unfortunately disappointed as it was highly acidic and difficult to drink (almost needed a cube of sugar which I almost never do with my coffee).

    This wasn't quite the experience I hoped for. I love their recipes and I really think they are famous for a reason. However my one time trip for their croissants and their coffee left me unimpressed. Perhaps I should just stick with their bread. Their service was quick, efficient and welcoming but I'd think twice about going back for pastries alone.

    1) Banana Cream Tarte (5/5):
    I was super fortunate to get the last banana cream tart on a Sunday at 2:30pm. And note, this is not a banana cream pie, it is a tart. The thick cracker crust has a warm and sweet crunch to it. For the main filling on top of the crust, you have the creamy banana cream and many slices of freshanana

    2) Morning Bun (5/5): Most people that come here order the morning bun. I see why! This worthy and hyped pastry is like a cinnamon roll croissant with an orange taste and coated in the perfect amount of cinnamon sugar. Love the flaky texture, and the refreshing and light orange flavor.

    Expect a wait when you come to Tartine but your tastebuds will be happily rewarded.

    Note: they also have fresh baked bread but that is only available after 4:30pm.

    6 check-ins

    With nearly 8000 reviews this bakery deserves another shout out.

    The ~8000th rave review +'s:
    + Consistent bake. I'm a patron over many years and the breads, morning bun, almond tea cake, and croissants just never disappoint.
    + Range. There is something for everyone. All calorific that range from sweet to savory. The quiche has a nice crust and fillings change from ham and potato to kale and sundried tomatoes to any other daily special.
    + Creative. Other than traditional flaky croissants (plain or chocolate), there are inventive cakes to consider.
    + Service. Pleasant and attentive especially since the line can snake to 20 people deep on Saturday morning at 8:30AM.
    + Cozy seating. If you can find a table, be ready to sit elbow to elbow. There is outdoor seating to people watch.

    The ~10th not-so-rave review -'s:
    - Matcha latte. Don't get it. Lukewarm and tasteless. Go to Stonemill Matcha on 16th and Valencia if you want a real matcha latte.
    - Lines. After all these years the deserved hype has not subsided. Expect to wait your turn.

    TIPS *'s:
    * Early risers get a seat.
    *Tartine Bread by Chad Robertson is a book for serious bread makers to own.
